7.1.1 - W11SR10: Ineffective Credential Management for Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:
•	0421; 0431; 0433 (Relating to the enforcement of password complexity, length, and rotation).
•	0974; 1173 (Relating to the management of local administrative accounts and credentials).
•	1401 (Relating to the secure storage and protection of authentication credentials).
Current Risk
A lack of effective password credential management—specifically regarding complexity, length, and rotation frequency—on stand-alone workstations presents a significant security vulnerability. For both local privileged and unprivileged accounts, the absence of enforced credential policies may lead to poor credential hygiene. This increases the risk of brute-force attacks or credential harvesting, potentially leading to the compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of the agency’s system and its data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Enforce Hardened Password Policies: Apply Group Policy Objects (GPO) or local security policies to all stand-alone images that mandate a minimum of 14 characters, complex character sets, and a defined rotation period in line with the ISM.
•	Implement Local Administrator Password Solution (LAPS): Where feasible for the environment, utilise a mechanism to ensure local administrator passwords are unique to each workstation and rotated automatically to prevent lateral movement.
•	User Security Awareness: Provide targeted guidance to users of stand-alone systems on the importance of unique, complex passphrases and the risks associated with credential sharing or improper storage.
- Treatment #1
•	Utilise the Microsoft Security Compliance Toolkit to deploy hardened account lockout and password history policies on all Windows 11 stand-alone endpoints.
•	Implement a "Physical Security Audit" process where local credential configurations are verified against the system security plan during quarterly inspections.
•	Mandate the use of approved, encrypted hardware-based password managers for users who must manage multiple local credentials in disconnected environments.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
Enforcing technical password constraints and ensuring unique local administrative credentials significantly reduces the efficacy of automated password attacks. While the management overhead of stand-alone accounts remains a factor, the likelihood of a successful credential-based compromise is reduced to "Unlikely." The consequence remains "Moderate," reflecting the potential impact of a single-system compromise.
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	MEDIUM

